title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SUFFOLK
initial speech: As by your high imperial majesty I had in charge at my depart for France, As procurator to your excellence, To marry Princess Margaret for your grace, So, in the famous ancient city, Tours, In presence of the Kings of France and Sicil, The Dukes of Orleans, Calaber, Bretagne and Alencon, Seven earls, twelve barons and twenty reverend bishops, I have perform'd my task and was espoused: And humbly now upon my bended knee, In sight of England and her lordly peers, Deliver up my title in the queen To your most gracious hands, that are the substance Of that great shadow I did represent; The happiest gift that ever marquess gave, The fairest queen that ever king received.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: KING HENRY VI
initial speech: Suffolk, arise. Welcome, Queen Margaret: I can express no kinder sign of love Than this kind kiss. O Lord, that lends me life, Lend me a heart replete with thankfulness! For thou hast given me in this beauteous face A world of earthly blessings to my soul, If sympathy of love unite our thoughts.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: QUEEN MARGARET
initial speech: Great King of England and my gracious lord, The mutual conference that my mind hath had, By day, by night, waking and in my dreams, In courtly company or at my beads, With you, mine alder-liefest sovereign, Makes me the bolder to salute my king With ruder terms, such as my wit affords And over-joy of heart doth minister.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: ALL
initial speech: happiness!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: GLOUCESTER
initial speech: king Charles, and William de la Pole, Marquess of Suffolk, ambassador for Henry King of England, that the said Henry shall espouse the Lady Margaret, daughter unto Reignier King of Naples, Sicilia and Jerusalem, and crown her Queen of England ere the thirtieth of May next ensuing. Item, that the duchy of Anjou and the county of Maine shall be released and delivered to the king her father'--

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CARDINAL
initial speech: that the duchies of Anjou and Maine shall be released and delivered over to the king her father, and she sent over of the King of England's own proper cost and charges, without having any dowry.'

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SALISBURY
initial speech: Now, by the death of Him that died for all, These counties were the keys of Normandy. But wherefore weeps Warwick, my valiant son?

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: WARWICK
initial speech: For grief that they are past recovery: For, were there hope to conquer them again, My sword should shed hot blood, mine eyes no tears. Anjou and Maine! myself did win them both; Those provinces these arms of mine did conquer: And are the cities, that I got with wounds, Delivered up again with peaceful words? Mort Dieu!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: YORK
initial speech: For Suffolk's duke, may he be suffocate, That dims the honour of this warlike isle! France should have torn and rent my very heart, Before I would have yielded to this league. I never read but England's kings have had Large sums of gold and dowries with their wives: And our King Henry gives away his own, To match with her that brings no vantages.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BUCKINGHAM
initial speech: Why should he, then, protect our sovereign, He being of age to govern of himself? Cousin of Somerset, join you with me, And all together, with the Duke of Suffolk, We'll quickly hoise Duke Humphrey from his seat.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SOMERSET
initial speech: Cousin of Buckingham, though Humphrey's pride And greatness of his place be grief to us, Yet let us watch the haughty cardinal: His insolence is more intolerable Than all the princes in the land beside: If Gloucester be displaced, he'll be protector.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: DUCHESS
initial speech: Why droops my lord, like over-ripen'd corn, Hanging the head at Ceres' plenteous load? Why doth the great Duke Humphrey knit his brows, As frowning at the favours of the world? Why are thine eyes fixed to the sullen earth, Gazing on that which seems to dim thy sight? What seest thou there? King Henry's diadem, Enchased with all the honours of the world? If so, gaze on, and grovel on thy face, Until thy head be circled with the same. Put forth thy hand, reach at the glorious gold. What, is't too short? I'll lengthen it with mine: And, having both together heaved it up, We'll both together lift our heads to heaven, And never more abase our sight so low As to vouchsafe one glance unto the ground.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Messenger
initial speech: My lord protector, 'tis his highness' pleasure You do prepare to ride unto Saint Alban's, Where as the king and queen do mean to hawk.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: HUME
initial speech: Jesus preserve your royal majesty!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Petitioner
initial speech: My masters, let's stand close: my lord protector will come this way by and by, and then we may deliver our supplications in the quill.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Petitioner
initial speech: Marry, the Lord protect him, for he's a good man! Jesu bless him!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: PETER
initial speech: Here a' comes, methinks, and the queen with him. I'll be the first, sure.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: HORNER
initial speech: An't shall please your majesty, I never said nor thought any such matter: God is my witness, I am falsely accused by the villain.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BOLINGBROKE
initial speech: Master Hume, we are therefore provided: will her ladyship behold and hear our exorcisms?

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Spirit
initial speech: Adsum.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: MARGARET JOURDAIN
initial speech: Asmath, By the eternal God, whose name and power Thou tremblest at, answer that I shall ask; For, till thou speak, thou shalt not pass from hence.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Townsman
initial speech: A miracle! a miracle!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SIMPCOX
initial speech: Born blind, an't please your grace.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Wife
initial speech: Ay, indeed, was he.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Mayor
initial speech: Yes, my lord, if it please your grace.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Beadle
initial speech: I will, my lord. Come on, sirrah; off with your doublet quickly.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BOTH
initial speech: Long live our sovereign Richard, England's king!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Neighbour
initial speech: Here, neighbour Horner, I drink to you in a cup of sack: and fear not, neighbour, you shall do well enough.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Neighbour
initial speech: And here, neighbour, here's a cup of charneco.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Third Neighbour
initial speech: And here's a pot of good double beer, neighbour: drink, and fear not your man.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First 'Prentice
initial speech: Here, Peter, I drink to thee: and be not afraid.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second 'Prentice
initial speech: Be merry, Peter, and fear not thy master: fight for credit of the 'prentices.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Servants
initial speech: Ten, my lord.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Servant
initial speech: So please your grace, we'll take her from the sheriff.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Herald
initial speech: I summon your grace to his majesty's parliament, Holden at Bury the first of this next month.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Sheriff
initial speech: An't please your grace, here my commission stays, And Sir John Stanley is appointed now To take her with him to the Isle of Man.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: STANLEY
initial speech: So am I given in charge, may't please your grace.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Post
initial speech: Great lords, from Ireland am I come amain, To signify that rebels there are up And put the Englishmen unto the sword: Send succors, lords, and stop the rage betime, Before the wound do grow uncurable; For, being green, there is great hope of help.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Murderer
initial speech: Run to my Lord of Suffolk; let him know We have dispatch'd the duke, as he commanded.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Murderer
initial speech: O that it were to do! What have we done? Didst ever hear a man so penitent?

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Murder
initial speech: Here comes my lord.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Commons
initial speech: Lord of Salisbury!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: VAUX
initial speech: To signify unto his majesty That Cardinal Beaufort is at point of death; For suddenly a grievous sickness took him, That makes him gasp and stare and catch the air, Blaspheming God and cursing men on earth. Sometimes he talks as if Duke Humphrey's ghost Were by his side; sometime he calls the king, And whispers to his pillow, as to him, The secrets of his overcharged soul; And I am sent to tell his majesty That even now he cries aloud for him.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Captain
initial speech: The gaudy, blabbing and remorseful day Is crept into the bosom of the sea; And now loud-howling wolves arouse the jades That drag the tragic melancholy night; Who, with their drowsy, slow and flagging wings, Clip dead men's graves and from their misty jaws Breathe foul contagious darkness in the air. Therefore bring forth the soldiers of our prize; For, whilst our pinnace anchors in the Downs, Here shall they make their ransom on the sand, Or with their blood stain this discolour'd shore. Master, this prisoner freely give I thee; And thou that art his mate, make boot of this; The other, Walter Whitmore, is thy share.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Gentleman
initial speech: What is my ransom, master? let me know.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Master
initial speech: A thousand crowns, or else lay down your head.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Master's-Mate
initial speech: And so much shall you give, or off goes yours.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Gentleman
initial speech: And so will I and write home for it straight.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: WHITMORE
initial speech: I lost mine eye in laying the prize aboard, And therefore to revenge it, shalt thou die; And so should these, if I might have my will.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BEVIS
initial speech: Come, and get thee a sword, though made of a lath; they have been up these two days.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: HOLLAND
initial speech: They have the more need to sleep now, then.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CADE
initial speech: We John Cade, so termed of our supposed father,--

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: DICK

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SMITH
initial speech: furred pack, she washes bucks here at home.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Clerk
initial speech: Emmanuel.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CLERK
initial speech: Sir, I thank God, I have been so well brought up that I can write my name.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: MICHAEL
initial speech: Where's our general?

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SIR HUMPHREY
initial speech: Rebellious hinds, the filth and scum of Kent, Mark'd for the gallows, lay your weapons down; Home to your cottages, forsake this groom: The king is merciful, if you revolt.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: WILLIAM STAFFORD
initial speech: But angry, wrathful, and inclined to blood, If you go forward; therefore yield, or die.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SAY
initial speech: Ay, but I hope your highness shall have his.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: SCALES
initial speech: How now! is Jack Cade slain?

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Citizen
initial speech: No, my lord, nor likely to be slain; for they have won the bridge, killing all those that withstand them: the lord mayor craves aid of your honour from the Tower, to defend the city from the rebels.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Soldier
initial speech: Jack Cade! Jack Cade!

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CLIFFORD
initial speech: What say ye, countrymen? will ye relent, And yield to mercy whilst 'tis offer'd you; Or let a rebel lead you to your deaths? Who loves the king and will embrace his pardon, Fling up his cap, and say 'God save his majesty!' Who hateth him and honours not his father, Henry the Fifth, that made all France to quake, Shake he his weapon at us and pass by.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: IDEN
initial speech: Lord, who would live turmoiled in the court, And may enjoy such quiet walks as these? This small inheritance my father left me Contenteth me, and worth a monarchy. I seek not to wax great by others' waning, Or gather wealth, I care not, with what envy: Sufficeth that I have maintains my state And sends the poor well pleased from my gate.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: EDWARD
initial speech: Ay, noble father, if our words will serve.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: RICHARD
initial speech: And if words will not, then our weapons shall.

title: The Second Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: YOUNG CLIFFORD
initial speech: And so to arms, victorious father, To quell the rebels and their complices.

title: As You Like It
speaker: ORLANDO
initial speech: As I remember, Adam, it was upon this fashion bequeathed me by will but poor a thousand crowns, and, as thou sayest, charged my brother, on his blessing, to breed me well: and there begins my sadness. My brother Jaques he keeps at school, and report speaks goldenly of his profit: for my part, he keeps me rustically at home, or, to speak more properly, stays me here at home unkept; for call you that keeping for a gentleman of my birth, that differs not from the stalling of an ox? His horses are bred better; for, besides that they are fair with their feeding, they are taught their manage, and to that end riders dearly hired: but I, his brother, gain nothing under him but growth; for the which his animals on his dunghills are as much bound to him as I. Besides this nothing that he so plentifully gives me, the something that nature gave me his countenance seems to take from me: he lets me feed with his hinds, bars me the place of a brother, and, as much as in him lies, mines my gentility with my education. This is it, Adam, that grieves me; and the spirit of my father, which I think is within me, begins to mutiny against this servitude: I will no longer endure it, though yet I know no wise remedy how to avoid it.

title: As You Like It
speaker: ADAM
initial speech: Yonder comes my master, your brother.

title: As You Like It
speaker: OLIVER
initial speech: Now, sir! what make you here?

title: As You Like It
speaker: DENNIS
initial speech: Calls your worship?

title: As You Like It
speaker: CHARLES
initial speech: Good morrow to your worship.

title: As You Like It
speaker: CELIA
initial speech: I pray thee, Rosalind, sweet my coz, be merry.

title: As You Like It
speaker: ROSALIND
initial speech: Dear Celia, I show more mirth than I am mistress of; and would you yet I were merrier? Unless you could teach me to forget a banished father, you must not learn me how to remember any extraordinary pleasure.

title: As You Like It
speaker: TOUCHSTONE
initial speech: Mistress, you must come away to your father.

title: As You Like It
speaker: LE BEAU
initial speech: Fair princess, you have lost much good sport.

title: As You Like It
speaker: DUKE FREDERICK
initial speech: Come on: since the youth will not be entreated, his own peril on his forwardness.

title: As You Like It
speaker: DUKE SENIOR
initial speech: Now, my co-mates and brothers in exile, Hath not old custom made this life more sweet Than that of painted pomp? Are not these woods More free from peril than the envious court? Here feel we but the penalty of Adam, The seasons' difference, as the icy fang And churlish chiding of the winter's wind, Which, when it bites and blows upon my body, Even till I shrink with cold, I smile and say 'This is no flattery: these are counsellors That feelingly persuade me what I am.' Sweet are the uses of adversity, Which, like the toad, ugly and venomous, Wears yet a precious jewel in his head; And this our life exempt from public haunt Finds tongues in trees, books in the running brooks, Sermons in stones and good in every thing. I would not change it.

title: As You Like It
speaker: AMIENS
initial speech: Happy is your grace, That can translate the stubbornness of fortune Into so quiet and so sweet a style.

title: As You Like It
speaker: First Lord
initial speech: Indeed, my lord, The melancholy Jaques grieves at that, And, in that kind, swears you do more usurp Than doth your brother that hath banish'd you. To-day my Lord of Amiens and myself Did steal behind him as he lay along Under an oak whose antique root peeps out Upon the brook that brawls along this wood: To the which place a poor sequester'd stag, That from the hunter's aim had ta'en a hurt, Did come to languish, and indeed, my lord, The wretched animal heaved forth such groans That their discharge did stretch his leathern coat Almost to bursting, and the big round tears Coursed one another down his innocent nose In piteous chase; and thus the hairy fool Much marked of the melancholy Jaques, Stood on the extremest verge of the swift brook, Augmenting it with tears.

title: As You Like It
speaker: Second Lord
initial speech: We did, my lord, weeping and commenting Upon the sobbing deer.

title: As You Like It
speaker: CORIN
initial speech: That is the way to make her scorn you still.

title: As You Like It
speaker: SILVIUS
initial speech: O Corin, that thou knew'st how I do love her!

title: As You Like It
speaker: JAQUES
initial speech: More, more, I prithee, more.

title: As You Like It
speaker: AUDREY
initial speech: Your features! Lord warrant us! what features!

title: As You Like It
speaker: SIR OLIVER MARTEXT
initial speech: Is there none here to give the woman?

title: As You Like It
speaker: PHEBE
initial speech: I would not be thy executioner: I fly thee, for I would not injure thee. Thou tell'st me there is murder in mine eye: 'Tis pretty, sure, and very probable, That eyes, that are the frail'st and softest things, Who shut their coward gates on atomies, Should be call'd tyrants, butchers, murderers! Now I do frown on thee with all my heart; And if mine eyes can wound, now let them kill thee: Now counterfeit to swoon; why now fall down; Or if thou canst not, O, for shame, for shame, Lie not, to say mine eyes are murderers! Now show the wound mine eye hath made in thee: Scratch thee but with a pin, and there remains Some scar of it; lean but upon a rush, The cicatrice and capable impressure Thy palm some moment keeps; but now mine eyes, Which I have darted at thee, hurt thee not, Nor, I am sure, there is no force in eyes That can do hurt.

title: As You Like It
speaker: A Lord
initial speech: Sir, it was I.

title: As You Like It
speaker: Forester
initial speech: Yes, sir.

title: As You Like It
speaker: WILLIAM
initial speech: Good even, Audrey.

title: As You Like It
speaker: First Page
initial speech: Well met, honest gentleman.

title: As You Like It
speaker: Second Page
initial speech: We are for you: sit i' the middle.

title: As You Like It
speaker: HYMEN
initial speech: Then is there mirth in heaven, When earthly things made even Atone together. Good duke, receive thy daughter Hymen from heaven brought her, Yea, brought her hither, That thou mightst join her hand with his Whose heart within his bosom is.

title: As You Like It
speaker: JAQUES DE BOYS
initial speech: Let me have audience for a word or two: I am the second son of old Sir Rowland, That bring these tidings to this fair assembly. Duke Frederick, hearing how that every day Men of great worth resorted to this forest, Address'd a mighty power; which were on foot, In his own conduct, purposely to take His brother here and put him to the sword: And to the skirts of this wild wood he came; Where meeting with an old religious man, After some question with him, was converted Both from his enterprise and from the world, His crown bequeathing to his banish'd brother, And all their lands restored to them again That were with him exiled. This to be true, I do engage my life.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: [GOWER]
initial speech: To sing a song that old was sung, From ashes ancient Gower is come; Assuming man's infirmities, To glad your ear, and please your eyes. It hath been sung at festivals, On ember-eves and holy-ales; And lords and ladies in their lives Have read it for restoratives: The purchase is to make men glorious; Et bonum quo antiquius, eo melius. If you, born in these latter times, When wit's more ripe, accept my rhymes. And that to hear an old man sing May to your wishes pleasure bring I life would wish, and that I might Waste it for you, like taper-light. This Antioch, then, Antiochus the Great Built up, this city, for his chiefest seat: The fairest in all Syria, I tell you what mine authors say: This king unto him took a fere, Who died and left a female heir, So buxom, blithe, and full of face, As heaven had lent her all his grace; With whom the father liking took, And her to incest did provoke: Bad child; worse father! to entice his own To evil should be done by none: But custom what they did begin Was with long use account no sin. The beauty of this sinful dame Made many princes thither frame, To seek her as a bed-fellow, In marriage-pleasures play-fellow: Which to prevent he made a law, To keep her still, and men in awe, That whoso ask'd her for his wife, His riddle told not, lost his life: So for her many a wight did die, As yon grim looks do testify. What now ensues, to the judgment of your eye I give, my cause who best can justify.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: ANTIOCHUS
initial speech: Young prince of Tyre, you have at large received The danger of the task you undertake.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: PERICLES
initial speech: I have, Antiochus, and, with a soul Embolden'd with the glory of her praise, Think death no hazard in this enterprise.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Daughter
initial speech: Of all say'd yet, mayst thou prove prosperous! Of all say'd yet, I wish thee happiness!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: THALIARD
initial speech: Doth your highness call?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: HELICANUS
initial speech: Peace, peace, and give experience tongue. They do abuse the king that flatter him: For flattery is the bellows blows up sin; The thing which is flatter'd, but a spark, To which that blast gives heat and stronger glowing; Whereas reproof, obedient and in order, Fits kings, as they are men, for they may err. When Signior Sooth here does proclaim a peace, He flatters you, makes war upon your life. Prince, pardon me, or strike me, if you please; I cannot be much lower than my knees.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: CLEON
initial speech: My Dionyza, shall we rest us here, And by relating tales of others' griefs, See if 'twill teach us to forget our own?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: DIONYZA
initial speech: That were to blow at fire in hope to quench it; For who digs hills because they do aspire Throws down one mountain to cast up a higher. O my distressed lord, even such our griefs are; Here they're but felt, and seen with mischief's eyes, But like to groves, being topp'd, they higher rise.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Lord
initial speech: Where's the lord governor?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: All
initial speech: The gods of Greece protect you! And we'll pray for you.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: GOWER
initial speech: Here have you seen a mighty king His child, I wis, to incest bring; A better prince and benign lord, That will prove awful both in deed and word. Be quiet then as men should be, Till he hath pass'd necessity. I'll show you those in troubles reign, Losing a mite, a mountain gain. The good in conversation, To whom I give my benison, Is still at Tarsus, where each man Thinks all is writ he speken can; And, to remember what he does, Build his statue to make him glorious: But tidings to the contrary Are brought your eyes; what need speak I? Good Helicane, that stay'd at home, Not to eat honey like a drone From others' labours; for though he strive To killen bad, keep good alive; And to fulfil his prince' desire, Sends word of all that haps in Tyre: How Thaliard came full bent with sin And had intent to murder him; And that in Tarsus was not best Longer for him to make his rest. He, doing so, put forth to seas, Where when men been, there's seldom ease; For now the wind begins to blow; Thunder above and deeps below Make such unquiet, that the ship Should house him safe is wreck'd and split; And he, good prince, having all lost, By waves from coast to coast is tost: All perishen of man, of pelf, Ne aught escapen but himself; Till fortune, tired with doing bad, Threw him ashore, to give him glad: And here he comes. What shall be next, Pardon old Gower,--this longs the text.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: First Fisherman
initial speech: What, ho, Pilch!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Second Fisherman
initial speech: Ha, come and bring away the nets!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Third Fisherman
initial speech: What say you, master?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: SIMONIDES
initial speech: Are the knights ready to begin the triumph?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: THAISA
initial speech: It pleaseth you, my royal father, to express My commendations great, whose merit's less.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Third Lord
initial speech: And on set purpose let his armour rust Until this day, to scour it in the dust.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: KNIGHTS
initial speech: We are honour'd much by good Simonides.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Marshal
initial speech: Sir, yonder is your place.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: First Knight
initial speech: Contend not, sir; for we are gentlemen That neither in our hearts nor outward eyes Envy the great nor do the low despise.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Knights
initial speech: Who can be other in this royal presence?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: ESCANES
initial speech: 'Twas very strange.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Second Knight
initial speech: May we not get access to her, my lord?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Third Knight
initial speech: Loath to bid farewell, we take our leaves.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: LYCHORIDA
initial speech: Here is a thing too young for such a place, Who, if it had conceit, would die, as I Am like to do: take in your arms this piece Of your dead queen.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: First Sailor
initial speech: What courage, sir? God save you!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Second Sailor
initial speech: But sea-room, an the brine and cloudy billow kiss the moon, I care not.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: CERIMON
initial speech: Philemon, ho!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: PHILEMON
initial speech: Doth my lord call?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: First Servant
initial speech: So; lift there.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: LEONINE
initial speech: I will do't; but yet she is a goodly creature.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: MARINA
initial speech: No, I will rob Tellus of her weed, To strew thy green with flowers: the yellows, blues, The purple violets, and marigolds, Shall as a carpet hang upon thy grave, While summer-days do last. Ay me! poor maid, Born in a tempest, when my mother died, This world to me is like a lasting storm, Whirring me from my friends.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: First Pirate
initial speech: Hold, villain!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Second Pirate
initial speech: A prize! a prize!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Third Pirate
initial speech: Half-part, mates, half-part. Come, let's have her aboard suddenly.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Pandar
initial speech: Boult!

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: BOULT
initial speech: Sir?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Bawd
initial speech: We were never so much out of creatures. We have but poor three, and they can do no more than they can do; and they with continual action are even as good as rotten.

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: LYSIMACHUS
initial speech: How now! How a dozen of virginities?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: Tyrian Sailor
initial speech: he can resolve you. O, here he is. Sir, there's a barge put off from Mytilene, And in it is Lysimachus the governor, Who craves to come aboard. What is your will?

title: Pericles, Prince of Tyre
speaker: DIANA
initial speech: My temple stands in Ephesus: hie thee thither, And do upon mine altar sacrifice. There, when my maiden priests are met together, Before the people all, Reveal how thou at sea didst lose thy wife: To mourn thy crosses, with thy daughter's, call And give them repetition to the life. Or perform my bidding, or thou livest in woe; Do it, and happy; by my silver bow! Awake, and tell thy dream.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: MONTAGUE
initial speech: And, brother, here's the Earl of Wiltshire's blood, Whom I encounter'd as the battles join'd.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: NORFOLK
initial speech: Such hope have all the line of John of Gaunt!

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: NORTHUMBERLAND
initial speech: If I be not, heavens be revenged on me!

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: WESTMORELAND
initial speech: What, shall we suffer this? let's pluck him down: My heart for anger burns; I cannot brook it.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: EXETER
initial speech: But when the duke is slain, they'll quickly fly.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: PRINCE EDWARD
initial speech: Father, you cannot disinherit me: If you be king, why should not I succeed?

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: JOHN MORTIMER
initial speech: She shall not need; we'll meet her in the field.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: RUTLAND
initial speech: Ah, whither shall I fly to 'scape their hands? Ah, tutor, look where bloody Clifford comes!

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Tutor
initial speech: And I, my lord, will bear him company.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: PRINCE
initial speech: My gracious father, by your kingly leave, I'll draw it as apparent to the crown, And in that quarrel use it to the death.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: GEORGE
initial speech: But when we saw our sunshine made thy spring, And that thy summer bred us no increase, We set the axe to thy usurping root; And though the edge hath something hit ourselves, Yet, know thou, since we have begun to strike, We'll never leave till we have hewn thee down, Or bathed thy growing with our heated bloods.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Son
initial speech: Ill blows the wind that profits nobody. This man, whom hand to hand I slew in fight, May be possessed with some store of crowns; And I, that haply take them from him now, May yet ere night yield both my life and them To some man else, as this dead man doth me. Who's this? O God! it is my father's face, Whom in this conflict I unwares have kill'd. O heavy times, begetting such events! From London by the king was I press'd forth; My father, being the Earl of Warwick's man, Came on the part of York, press'd by his master; And I, who at his hands received my life, him Have by my hands of life bereaved him. Pardon me, God, I knew not what I did! And pardon, father, for I knew not thee! My tears shall wipe away these bloody marks; And no more words till they have flow'd their fill.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Father
initial speech: Thou that so stoutly hast resisted me, Give me thy gold, if thou hast any gold: For I have bought it with an hundred blows. But let me see: is this our foeman's face? Ah, no, no, no, it is mine only son! Ah, boy, if any life be left in thee, Throw up thine eye! see, see what showers arise, Blown with the windy tempest of my heart, Upon thy words, that kill mine eye and heart! O, pity, God, this miserable age! What stratagems, how fell, how butcherly, Erroneous, mutinous and unnatural, This deadly quarrel daily doth beget! O boy, thy father gave thee life too soon, And hath bereft thee of thy life too late!

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Keeper
initial speech: Under this thick-grown brake we'll shroud ourselves; For through this laund anon the deer will come; And in this covert will we make our stand, Culling the principal of all the deer.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Keeper
initial speech: I'll stay above the hill, so both may shoot.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: KING EDWARD IV
initial speech: Brother of Gloucester, at Saint Alban's field This lady's husband, Sir Richard Grey, was slain, His lands then seized on by the conqueror: Her suit is now to repossess those lands; Which we in justice cannot well deny, Because in quarrel of the house of York The worthy gentleman did lose his life.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CLARENCE
initial speech: he keeps the wind!

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: LADY GREY
initial speech: Right gracious lord, I cannot brook delay: May it please your highness to resolve me now; And what your pleasure is, shall satisfy me.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Nobleman
initial speech: My gracious lord, Henry your foe is taken, And brought your prisoner to your palace gate.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: KING LEWIS XI
initial speech: Fair Queen of England, worthy Margaret, Sit down with us: it ill befits thy state And birth, that thou shouldst stand while Lewis doth sit.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: OXFORD
initial speech: Then Warwick disannuls great John of Gaunt, Which did subdue the greatest part of Spain; And, after John of Gaunt, Henry the Fourth, Whose wisdom was a mirror to the wisest; And, after that wise prince, Henry the Fifth, Who by his prowess conquered all France: From these our Henry lineally descends.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BONA
initial speech: Your grant, or your denial, shall be mine: Yet I confess that often ere this day, When I have heard your king's desert recounted, Mine ear hath tempted judgment to desire.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: HASTINGS
initial speech: Why, knows not Montague that of itself England is safe, if true within itself?

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: QUEEN ELIZABETH
initial speech: My lords, before it pleased his majesty To raise my state to title of a queen, Do me but right, and you must all confess That I was not ignoble of descent; And meaner than myself have had like fortune. But as this title honours me and mine, So your dislike, to whom I would be pleasing, Doth cloud my joys with danger and with sorrow.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Watchman
initial speech: Come on, my masters, each man take his stand: The king by this is set him down to sleep.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Watchman
initial speech: What, will he not to bed?

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Third Watchman
initial speech: But say, I pray, what nobleman is that That with the king here resteth in his tent?

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: RIVERS
initial speech: Madam, what makes you in this sudden change?

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Huntsman
initial speech: This way, my lord; for this way lies the game.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Lieutenant
initial speech: Subjects may challenge nothing of their sovereigns; But if an humble prayer may prevail, I then crave pardon of your majesty.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Messenger
initial speech: By this at Dunsmore, marching hitherward.

title: The Third Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Messenger
initial speech: By this at Daintry, with a puissant troop.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BEDFORD
initial speech: Hung be the heavens with black, yield day to night! Comets, importing change of times and states, Brandish your crystal tresses in the sky, And with them scourge the bad revolting stars That have consented unto Henry's death! King Henry the Fifth, too famous to live long! England ne'er lost a king of so much worth.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BISHOP OF WINCHESTER
initial speech: He was a king bless'd of the King of kings. Unto the French the dreadful judgement-day So dreadful will not be as was his sight. The battles of the Lord of hosts he fought: The church's prayers made him so prosperous.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: ALENCON
initial speech: They want their porridge and their fat bull-beeves: Either they must be dieted like mules And have their provender tied to their mouths Or piteous they will look, like drowned mice.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: REIGNIER
initial speech: Let's raise the siege: why live we idly here? Talbot is taken, whom we wont to fear: Remaineth none but mad-brain'd Salisbury; And he may well in fretting spend his gall, Nor men nor money hath he to make war.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BASTARD OF ORLEANS
initial speech: Where's the Prince Dauphin? I have news for him.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: JOAN LA PUCELLE
initial speech: Reignier, is't thou that thinkest to beguile me? Where is the Dauphin? Come, come from behind; I know thee well, though never seen before. Be not amazed, there's nothing hid from me: In private will I talk with thee apart. Stand back, you lords, and give us leave awhile.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Warder

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Serving-Man
initial speech: It is the noble Duke of Gloucester.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Warder

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: WOODVILE
initial speech: What noise is this? what traitors have we here?

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Serving-Men
initial speech: Open the gates unto the lord protector, Or we'll burst them open, if that you come not quickly.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Officer
initial speech: All manner of men assembled here in arms this day against God's peace and the king's, we charge and command you, in his highness' name, to repair to your several dwelling-places; and not to wear, handle, or use any sword, weapon, or dagger, henceforward, upon pain of death.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Master-Gunner
initial speech: Sirrah, thou know'st how Orleans is besieged, And how the English have the suburbs won.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Boy
initial speech: Father, I know; and oft have shot at them, Howe'er unfortunate I miss'd my aim.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: TALBOT
initial speech: The Duke of Bedford had a prisoner Call'd the brave Lord Ponton de Santrailles; For him was I exchanged and ransomed. But with a baser man of arms by far Once in contempt they would have barter'd me: Which I, disdaining, scorn'd; and craved death, Rather than I would be so vile esteem'd. In fine, redeem'd I was as I desired. But, O! the treacherous Fastolfe wounds my heart, Whom with my bare fists I would execute, If I now had him brought into my power.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: GARGRAVE
initial speech: I think, at the north gate; for there stand lords.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: GLANSDALE
initial speech: And I, here, at the bulwark of the bridge.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Sergeant
initial speech: Sirs, take your places and be vigilant: If any noise or soldier you perceive Near to the walls, by some apparent sign Let us have knowledge at the court of guard.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Sentinel
initial speech: Sergeant, you shall. Thus are poor servitors, When others sleep upon their quiet beds, Constrain'd to watch in darkness, rain and cold.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BURGUNDY
initial speech: Traitors have never other company. But what's that Pucelle whom they term so pure?

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Sentinels
initial speech: Arm! arm! the enemy doth make assault!

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: COUNTESS OF AUVERGNE
initial speech: Porter, remember what I gave in charge; And when you have done so, bring the keys to me.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Porter
initial speech: Madam, I will.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: RICHARD PLANTAGENET
initial speech: Great lords and gentlemen, what means this silence? Dare no man answer in a case of truth?

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: VERNON
initial speech: Stay, lords and gentlemen, and pluck no more, Till you conclude that he upon whose side The fewest roses are cropp'd from the tree Shall yield the other in the right opinion.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Lawyer
initial speech: Unless my study and my books be false, The argument you held was wrong in you: In sign whereof I pluck a white rose too.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: MORTIMER
initial speech: Kind keepers of my weak decaying age, Let dying Mortimer here rest himself. Even like a man new haled from the rack, So fare my limbs with long imprisonment. And these grey locks, the pursuivants of death, Nestor-like aged in an age of care, Argue the end of Edmund Mortimer. These eyes, like lamps whose wasting oil is spent, Wax dim, as drawing to their exigent; Weak shoulders, overborne with burthening grief, And pithless arms, like to a wither'd vine That droops his sapless branches to the ground; Yet are these feet, whose strengthless stay is numb, Unable to support this lump of clay, Swift-winged with desire to get a grave, As witting I no other comfort have. But tell me, keeper, will my nephew come?

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Gaoler
initial speech: Richard Plantagenet, my lord, will come: We sent unto the Temple, unto his chamber; And answer was return'd that he will come.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Serving-man
initial speech: Nay, if we be forbidden stones, We'll fall to it with our teeth.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Second Serving-man
initial speech: Do what ye dare, we are as resolute.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Third Serving-man
initial speech: My lord, we know your grace to be a man Just and upright; and, for your royal birth, Inferior to none but to his majesty: And ere that we will suffer such a prince, So kind a father of the commonweal, To be disgraced by an inkhorn mate, We and our wives and children all will fight And have our bodies slaughtered by thy foes.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: First Soldier
initial speech: Our sacks shall be a mean to sack the city, And we be lords and rulers over Rouen; Therefore we'll knock.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Watch

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: FASTOLFE
initial speech: Whither away! to save myself by flight: We are like to have the overthrow again.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: BASSET
initial speech: Yes, sir; as well as you dare patronage The envious barking of your saucy tongue Against my lord the Duke of Somerset.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: General
initial speech: Thou ominous and fearful owl of death, Our nation's terror and their bloody scourge! The period of thy tyranny approacheth. On us thou canst not enter but by death; For, I protest, we are well fortified And strong enough to issue out and fight: If thou retire, the Dauphin, well appointed, Stands with the snares of war to tangle thee: On either hand thee there are squadrons pitch'd, To wall thee from the liberty of flight; And no way canst thou turn thee for redress, But death doth front thee with apparent spoil And pale destruction meets thee in the face. Ten thousand French have ta'en the sacrament To rive their dangerous artillery Upon no Christian soul but English Talbot. Lo, there thou stand'st, a breathing valiant man, Of an invincible unconquer'd spirit! This is the latest glory of thy praise That I, thy enemy, due thee withal; For ere the glass, that now begins to run, Finish the process of his sandy hour, These eyes, that see thee now well coloured, Shall see thee wither'd, bloody, pale and dead. Hark! hark! the Dauphin's drum, a warning bell, Sings heavy music to thy timorous soul; And mine shall ring thy dire departure out.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: LUCY
initial speech: Thou princely leader of our English strength, Never so needful on the earth of France, Spur to the rescue of the noble Talbot, Who now is girdled with a waist of iron And hemm'd about with grim destruction: To Bourdeaux, warlike duke! to Bourdeaux, York! Else, farewell Talbot, France, and England's honour.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: JOHN TALBOT
initial speech: Is my name Talbot? and am I your son? And shall I fly? O if you love my mother, Dishonour not her honourable name, To make a bastard and a slave of me! The world will say, he is not Talbot's blood, That basely fled when noble Talbot stood.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: CARDINAL OF WINCHESTER
initial speech: Stay, my lord legate: you shall first receive The sum of money which I promised Should be deliver'd to his holiness For clothing me in these grave ornaments.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Legate
initial speech: I will attend upon your lordship's leisure.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Scout
initial speech: Success unto our valiant general, And happiness to his accomplices!

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: MARGARET
initial speech: Margaret my name, and daughter to a king, The King of Naples, whosoe'er thou art.

title: The First Part of Henry the Sixth
speaker: Shepherd
initial speech: Ah, Joan, this kills thy father's heart outright! Have I sought every country far and near, And, now it is my chance to find thee out, Must I behold thy timeless cruel death? Ah, Joan, sweet daughter Joan, I'll die with thee!

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Poet
initial speech: Good day, sir.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Painter
initial speech: I am glad you're well.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Merchant
initial speech: O, 'tis a worthy lord.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Jeweller
initial speech: Nay, that's most fix'd.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Jeweller:
initial speech: I have a jewel here--

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: TIMON
initial speech: Imprison'd is he, say you?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Old Athenian
initial speech: Lord Timon, hear me speak.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: LUCILIUS
initial speech: Here, at your lordship's service.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: APEMANTUS
initial speech: Till I be gentle, stay thou for thy good morrow; When thou art Timon's dog, and these knaves honest.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: ALCIBIADES
initial speech: Sir, you have saved my longing, and I feed Most hungerly on your sight.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: VENTIDIUS
initial speech: Most honour'd Timon, It hath pleased the gods to remember my father's age, And call him to long peace. He is gone happy, and has left me rich: Then, as in grateful virtue I am bound To your free heart, I do return those talents, Doubled with thanks and service, from whose help I derived liberty.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Cupid
initial speech: Hail to thee, worthy Timon, and to all That of his bounties taste! The five best senses Acknowledge thee their patron; and come freely To gratulate thy plenteous bosom: th' ear, Taste, touch and smell, pleased from thy tale rise; They only now come but to feast thine eyes.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: First Lady
initial speech: My lord, you take us even at the best.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: All Ladies
initial speech: Most thankfully, my lord.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: FLAVIUS
initial speech: My lord?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Second Servant
initial speech: May it please your honour, Lord Lucius, Out of his free love, hath presented to you Four milk-white horses, trapp'd in silver.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Third Servant
initial speech: Please you, my lord, that honourable gentleman, Lord Lucullus, entreats your company to-morrow to hunt with him, and has sent your honour two brace of greyhounds.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: All Lords
initial speech: O, none so welcome.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Senator
initial speech: And late, five thousand: to Varro and to Isidore He owes nine thousand; besides my former sum, Which makes it five and twenty. Still in motion Of raging waste? It cannot hold; it will not. If I want gold, steal but a beggar's dog, And give it Timon, why, the dog coins gold. If I would sell my horse, and buy twenty more Better than he, why, give my horse to Timon, Ask nothing, give it him, it foals me, straight, And able horses. No porter at his gate, But rather one that smiles and still invites All that pass by. It cannot hold: no reason Can found his state in safety. Caphis, ho! Caphis, I say!

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: CAPHIS
initial speech: Here, sir; what is your pleasure?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Varro's Servant
initial speech: Is't not your business too?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Isidore's Servant
initial speech: It is so.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: All Servants
initial speech: What are we, Apemantus?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Fool
initial speech: How do you, gentlemen?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Page
initial speech: in this wise company? How dost thou, Apemantus?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: FLAMINIUS
initial speech: As you have said, my lord.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: LUCULLUS
initial speech: warrant. Why, this hits right; I dreamt of a silver basin and ewer to-night. Flaminius, honest Flaminius; you are very respectively welcome, sir. Fill me some wine. And how does that honourable, complete, free-hearted gentleman of Athens, thy very bountiful good lord and master?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: First Stranger
initial speech: We know him for no less, though we are but strangers to him. But I can tell you one thing, my lord, and which I hear from common rumours: now Lord Timon's happy hours are done and past, and his estate shrinks from him.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Second Stranger
initial speech: But believe you this, my lord, that, not long ago, one of his men was with the Lord Lucullus to borrow so many talents, nay, urged extremely for't and showed what necessity belonged to't, and yet was denied.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: SERVILIUS
initial speech: See, by good hap, yonder's my lord; I have sweat to see his honour. My honoured lord,--

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Third Stranger
initial speech: Religion groans at it.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: SEMPRONIUS
initial speech: Must he needs trouble me in 't,--hum!--'bove all others? He might have tried Lord Lucius or Lucullus; And now Ventidius is wealthy too, Whom he redeem'd from prison: all these Owe their estates unto him.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Varro's First Servant
initial speech: Well met; good morrow, Titus and Hortensius.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: TITUS
initial speech: The like to you kind Varro.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: HORTENSIUS
initial speech: Lucius! What, do we meet together?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Lucilius' Servant
initial speech: Ay, and I think One business does command us all; for mine Is money.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: PHILOTUS
initial speech: Good day at once.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Varro's Second Servant
initial speech: By your leave, sir,--

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Both Varro's Servants
initial speech: And ours, my lord.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: First Senator
initial speech: My lord, you have my voice to it; the fault's Bloody; 'tis necessary he should die: Nothing emboldens sin so much as mercy.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Second Senator
initial speech: Most true; the law shall bruise him.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Third Senator
initial speech: What!

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Some Speak
initial speech: What does his lordship mean?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Some Others
initial speech: I know not.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Fourth Lord
initial speech: I have lost my gown.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: PHRYNIA
initial speech: Thy lips rot off!

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: TIMANDRA
initial speech: Is this the Athenian minion, whom the world Voiced so regardfully?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: First Bandit
initial speech: Where should he have this gold? It is some poor fragment, some slender sort of his remainder: the mere want of gold, and the falling-from of his friends, drove him into this melancholy.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Second Bandit
initial speech: It is noised he hath a mass of treasure.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Third Bandit
initial speech: Let us make the assay upon him: if he care not for't, he will supply us easily; if he covetously reserve it, how shall's get it?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Banditti
initial speech: Where?

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: Both
initial speech: What we can do, we'll do, to do you service.

title: The Life of Timon of Athens
speaker: First Senator
initial speech: Set but thy foot Against our rampired gates, and they shall ope; So thou wilt send thy gentle heart before, To say thou'lt enter friendly.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: AEGEON
initial speech: Proceed, Solinus, to procure my fall And by the doom of death end woes and all.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: DUKE SOLINUS
initial speech: Merchant of Syracuse, plead no more; I am not partial to infringe our laws: The enmity and discord which of late Sprung from the rancorous outrage of your duke To merchants, our well-dealing countrymen, Who wanting guilders to redeem their lives Have seal'd his rigorous statutes with their bloods, Excludes all pity from our threatening looks. For, since the mortal and intestine jars 'Twixt thy seditious countrymen and us, It hath in solemn synods been decreed Both by the Syracusians and ourselves, To admit no traffic to our adverse towns Nay, more, If any born at Ephesus be seen At any Syracusian marts and fairs; Again: if any Syracusian born Come to the bay of Ephesus, he dies, His goods confiscate to the duke's dispose, Unless a thousand marks be levied, To quit the penalty and to ransom him. Thy substance, valued at the highest rate, Cannot amount unto a hundred marks; Therefore by law thou art condemned to die.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: Gaoler
initial speech: I will, my lord.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: First Merchant
initial speech: Therefore give out you are of Epidamnum, Lest that your goods too soon be confiscate. This very day a Syracusian merchant Is apprehended for arrival here; And not being able to buy out his life According to the statute of the town, Dies ere the weary sun set in the west. There is your money that I had to keep.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: ANTIPHOLUS OF SYRACUSE
initial speech: Go bear it to the Centaur, where we host, And stay there, Dromio, till I come to thee. Within this hour it will be dinner-time: Till that, I'll view the manners of the town, Peruse the traders, gaze upon the buildings, And then return and sleep within mine inn, For with long travel I am stiff and weary. Get thee away.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: DROMIO OF SYRACUSE
initial speech: Many a man would take you at your word, And go indeed, having so good a mean.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: DROMIO OF EPHESUS
initial speech: Return'd so soon! rather approach'd too late: The capon burns, the pig falls from the spit, The clock hath strucken twelve upon the bell; My mistress made it one upon my cheek: She is so hot because the meat is cold; The meat is cold because you come not home; You come not home because you have no stomach; You have no stomach having broke your fast; But we that know what 'tis to fast and pray Are penitent for your default to-day.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: ADRIANA
initial speech: Neither my husband nor the slave return'd, That in such haste I sent to seek his master! Sure, Luciana, it is two o'clock.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: LUCIANA
initial speech: Perhaps some merchant hath invited him, And from the mart he's somewhere gone to dinner. Good sister, let us dine and never fret: A man is master of his liberty: Time is their master, and, when they see time, They'll go or come: if so, be patient, sister.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: OF EPHESUS
initial speech: Good Signior Angelo, you must excuse us all; My wife is shrewish when I keep not hours: Say that I linger'd with you at your shop To see the making of her carcanet, And that to-morrow you will bring it home. But here's a villain that would face me down He met me on the mart, and that I beat him, And charged him with a thousand marks in gold, And that I did deny my wife and house. Thou drunkard, thou, what didst thou mean by this?

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: ANTIPHOLUS OF EPHESUS
initial speech: I think thou art an ass.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: BALTHAZAR
initial speech: I hold your dainties cheap, sir, and your welcome dear.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: LUCE
initial speech: at the gate?

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: ANGELO
initial speech: Here is neither cheer, sir, nor welcome: we would fain have either.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: Second Merchant
initial speech: You know since Pentecost the sum is due, And since I have not much importuned you; Nor now I had not, but that I am bound To Persia, and want guilders for my voyage: Therefore make present satisfaction, Or I'll attach you by this officer.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: Courtezan
initial speech: Well met, well met, Master Antipholus. I see, sir, you have found the goldsmith now: Is that the chain you promised me to-day?

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: PINCH
initial speech: Give me your hand and let me feel your pulse.

title: The Comedy of Errors
speaker: AEMELIA
initial speech: Be quiet, people. Wherefore throng you hither?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
initial speech: Two households, both alike in dignity, In fair Verona, where we lay our scene, From ancient grudge break to new mutiny, Where civil blood makes civil hands unclean. From forth the fatal loins of these two foes A pair of star-cross'd lovers take their life; Whole misadventured piteous overthrows Do with their death bury their parents' strife. The fearful passage of their death-mark'd love, And the continuance of their parents' rage, Which, but their children's end, nought could remove, Is now the two hours' traffic of our stage; The which if you with patient ears attend, What here shall miss, our toil shall strive to mend.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: SAMPSON
initial speech: Gregory, o' my word, we'll not carry coals.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: GREGORY
initial speech: No, for then we should be colliers.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: ABRAHAM
initial speech: Do you bite your thumb at us, sir?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: BENVOLIO
initial speech: Part, fools! Put up your swords; you know not what you do.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: TYBALT
initial speech: What, art thou drawn among these heartless hinds? Turn thee, Benvolio, look upon thy death.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: CAPULET
initial speech: What noise is this? Give me my long sword, ho!

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: LADY CAPULET
initial speech: A crutch, a crutch! why call you for a sword?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: LADY MONTAGUE
initial speech: Thou shalt not stir a foot to seek a foe.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: ROMEO
initial speech: Is the day so young?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: PARIS
initial speech: Of honourable reckoning are you both; And pity 'tis you lived at odds so long. But now, my lord, what say you to my suit?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Nurse
initial speech: Now, by my maidenhead, at twelve year old, I bade her come. What, lamb! what, ladybird! God forbid! Where's this girl? What, Juliet!

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: JULIET
initial speech: How now! who calls?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: MERCUTIO
initial speech: Nay, gentle Romeo, we must have you dance.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Second Capulet
initial speech: By'r lady, thirty years.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Chorus
initial speech: Now old desire doth in his death-bed lie, And young affection gapes to be his heir; That fair for which love groan'd for and would die, With tender Juliet match'd, is now not fair. Now Romeo is beloved and loves again, Alike betwitched by the charm of looks, But to his foe supposed he must complain, And she steal love's sweet bait from fearful hooks: Being held a foe, he may not have access To breathe such vows as lovers use to swear; And she as much in love, her means much less To meet her new-beloved any where: But passion lends them power, time means, to meet Tempering extremities with extreme sweet.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: FRIAR LAURENCE
initial speech: The grey-eyed morn smiles on the frowning night, Chequering the eastern clouds with streaks of light, And flecked darkness like a drunkard reels From forth day's path and Titan's fiery wheels: Now, ere the sun advance his burning eye, The day to cheer and night's dank dew to dry, I must up-fill this osier cage of ours With baleful weeds and precious-juiced flowers. The earth that's nature's mother is her tomb; What is her burying grave that is her womb, And from her womb children of divers kind We sucking on her natural bosom find, Many for many virtues excellent, None but for some and yet all different. O, mickle is the powerful grace that lies In herbs, plants, stones, and their true qualities: For nought so vile that on the earth doth live But to the earth some special good doth give, Nor aught so good but strain'd from that fair use Revolts from true birth, stumbling on abuse: Virtue itself turns vice, being misapplied; And vice sometimes by action dignified. Within the infant rind of this small flower Poison hath residence and medicine power: For this, being smelt, with that part cheers each part; Being tasted, slays all senses with the heart. Two such opposed kings encamp them still In man as well as herbs, grace and rude will; And where the worser is predominant, Full soon the canker death eats up that plant.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: NURSE
initial speech: Well, sir; my mistress is the sweetest lady--Lord, Lord! when 'twas a little prating thing:--O, there is a nobleman in town, one Paris, that would fain lay knife aboard; but she, good soul, had as lief see a toad, a very toad, as see him. I anger her sometimes and tell her that Paris is the properer man; but, I'll warrant you, when I say so, she looks as pale as any clout in the versal world. Doth not rosemary and Romeo begin both with a letter?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: LADY  CAPULET
initial speech: We shall be short in our provision: 'Tis now near night.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: First Musician
initial speech: Faith, we may put up our pipes, and be gone.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Second Musician
initial speech: Pray you, put up your dagger, and put out your wit.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Musician
initial speech: Marry, sir, because silver hath a sweet sound.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Third Musician
initial speech: Faith, I know not what to say.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: BALTHASAR
initial speech: Then she is well, and nothing can be ill: Her body sleeps in Capel's monument, And her immortal part with angels lives. I saw her laid low in her kindred's vault, And presently took post to tell it you: O, pardon me for bringing these ill news, Since you did leave it for my office, sir.

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: Apothecary
initial speech: Who calls so loud?

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: FRIAR JOHN
initial speech: Holy Franciscan friar! brother, ho!

title: The Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet
speaker: PAGE
initial speech: Here in the churchyard; yet I will adventure.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: SLY
initial speech: I'll pheeze you, in faith.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Hostess
initial speech: A pair of stocks, you rogue!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: First Huntsman
initial speech: Why, Belman is as good as he, my lord; He cried upon it at the merest loss And twice to-day pick'd out the dullest scent: Trust me, I take him for the better dog.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Second Huntsman
initial speech: He breathes, my lord. Were he not warm'd with ale, This were a bed but cold to sleep so soundly.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Players
initial speech: We thank your honour.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: A Player
initial speech: So please your lordship to accept our duty.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: LUCENTIO
initial speech: Tranio, since for the great desire I had To see fair Padua, nursery of arts, I am arrived for fruitful Lombardy, The pleasant garden of great Italy; And by my father's love and leave am arm'd With his good will and thy good company, My trusty servant, well approved in all, Here let us breathe and haply institute A course of learning and ingenious studies. Pisa renown'd for grave citizens Gave me my being and my father first, A merchant of great traffic through the world, Vincetino come of Bentivolii. Vincetino's son brought up in Florence It shall become to serve all hopes conceived, To deck his fortune with his virtuous deeds: And therefore, Tranio, for the time I study, Virtue and that part of philosophy Will I apply that treats of happiness By virtue specially to be achieved. Tell me thy mind; for I have Pisa left And am to Padua come, as he that leaves A shallow plash to plunge him in the deep And with satiety seeks to quench his thirst.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: TRANIO
initial speech: Mi perdonato, gentle master mine, I am in all affected as yourself; Glad that you thus continue your resolve To suck the sweets of sweet philosophy. Only, good master, while we do admire This virtue and this moral discipline, Let's be no stoics nor no stocks, I pray; Or so devote to Aristotle's cheques As Ovid be an outcast quite abjured: Balk logic with acquaintance that you have And practise rhetoric in your common talk; Music and poesy use to quicken you; The mathematics and the metaphysics, Fall to them as you find your stomach serves you; No profit grows where is no pleasure ta'en: In brief, sir, study what you most affect.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: BAPTISTA
initial speech: Gentlemen, importune me no farther, For how I firmly am resolved you know; That is, not bestow my youngest daughter Before I have a husband for the elder: If either of you both love Katharina, Because I know you well and love you well, Leave shall you have to court her at your pleasure.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: GREMIO
initial speech: There, There, Hortensio, will you any wife?

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: KATHARINA
initial speech: I pray you, sir, is it your will To make a stale of me amongst these mates?

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: HORTENSIO
initial speech: Mates, maid! how mean you that? no mates for you, Unless you were of gentler, milder mould.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: HORTENSIA
initial speech: From all such devils, good Lord deliver us!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: BIANCA
initial speech: Sister, content you in my discontent. Sir, to your pleasure humbly I subscribe: My books and instruments shall be my company, On them to took and practise by myself.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: BIONDELLO
initial speech: Where have I been! Nay, how now! where are you? Master, has my fellow Tranio stolen your clothes? Or you stolen his? or both? pray, what's the news?

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: PETRUCHIO
initial speech: Verona, for a while I take my leave, To see my friends in Padua, but of all My best beloved and approved friend, Hortensio; and I trow this is his house. Here, sirrah Grumio; knock, I say.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: GRUMIO
initial speech: Knock, sir! whom should I knock? is there man has rebused your worship?

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: KATARINA
initial speech: Gentlemen, forward to the bridal dinner: I see a woman may be made a fool, If she had not a spirit to resist.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: CURTIS
initial speech: Who is that calls so coldly?

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: NATHANIEL
initial speech: Welcome home, Grumio!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: PHILIP
initial speech: How now, Grumio!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: JOSEPH
initial speech: What, Grumio!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: NICHOLAS
initial speech: Fellow Grumio!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: ALL SERVING-MEN
initial speech: Here, here, sir; here, sir.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Pedant
initial speech: God save you, sir!

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Haberdasher
initial speech: Here is the cap your worship did bespeak.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Tailor
initial speech: You bid me make it orderly and well, According to the fashion and the time.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: VINCENTIO
initial speech: Fair sir, and you my merry mistress, That with your strange encounter much amazed me, My name is call'd Vincentio; my dwelling Pisa; And bound I am to Padua; there to visit A son of mine, which long I have not seen.

title: The Taming of the Shrew
speaker: Widow
initial speech: Then never trust me, if I be afeard.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Citizen
initial speech: One word, good citizens.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: MENENIUS
initial speech: What work's, my countrymen, in hand? where go you With bats and clubs? The matter? speak, I pray you.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: MARCIUS
initial speech: Thanks. What's the matter, you dissentious rogues, That, rubbing the poor itch of your opinion, Make yourselves scabs?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: COMINIUS
initial speech: You have fought together.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: SICINIUS
initial speech: Was ever man so proud as is this Marcius?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: BRUTUS
initial speech: He has no equal.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: AUFIDIUS
initial speech: Is it not yours? What ever have been thought on in this state, That could be brought to bodily act ere Rome Had circumvention? 'Tis not four days gone Since I heard thence; these are the words: I think I have the letter here; yes, here it is. 'They have press'd a power, but it is not known Whether for east or west: the dearth is great; The people mutinous; and it is rumour'd, Cominius, Marcius your old enemy, Who is of Rome worse hated than of you, And Titus Lartius, a most valiant Roman, These three lead on this preparation Whither 'tis bent: most likely 'tis for you: Consider of it.'

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: VOLUMNIA
initial speech: I pray you, daughter, sing; or express yourself in a more comfortable sort: if my son were my husband, I should freelier rejoice in that absence wherein he won honour than in the embracements of his bed where he would show most love. When yet he was but tender-bodied and the only son of my womb, when youth with comeliness plucked all gaze his way, when for a day of kings' entreaties a mother should not sell him an hour from her beholding, I, considering how honour would become such a person. that it was no better than picture-like to hang by the wall, if renown made it not stir, was pleased to let him seek danger where he was like to find fame. To a cruel war I sent him; from whence he returned, his brows bound with oak. I tell thee, daughter, I sprang not more in joy at first hearing he was a man-child than now in first seeing he had proved himself a man.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: VIRGILIA
initial speech: But had he died in the business, madam; how then?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Gentlewoman
initial speech: Madam, the Lady Valeria is come to visit you.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: VALERIA
initial speech: My ladies both, good day to you.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: LARTIUS
initial speech: My horse to yours, no.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Soldier
initial speech: Nor I.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: First Roman
initial speech: This will I carry to Rome.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Roman
initial speech: And I this.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Third Roman
initial speech: A murrain on't! I took this for silver.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: CORIOLANUS
initial speech: I will go wash; And when my face is fair, you shall perceive Whether I blush or no: howbeit, I thank you. I mean to stride your steed, and at all times To undercrest your good addition To the fairness of my power.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: First Officer
initial speech: Come, come, they are almost here. How many stand for consulships?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Officer
initial speech: Three, they say: but 'tis thought of every one Coriolanus will carry it.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Senators
initial speech: To Coriolanus come all joy and honour!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Third Citizen
initial speech: We have power in ourselves to do it, but it is a power that we have no power to do; for if he show us his wounds and tell us his deeds, we are to put our tongues into those wounds and speak for them; so, if he tell us his noble deeds, we must also tell him our noble acceptance of them. Ingratitude is monstrous, and for the multitude to be ingrateful, were to make a monster of the multitude: of the which we being members, should bring ourselves to be monstrous members.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Fourth Citizen
initial speech: You have deserved nobly of your country, and you have not deserved nobly.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Fifth Citizen
initial speech: We hope to find you our friend; and therefore give you our voices heartily.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Both Citizens
initial speech: The gods give you joy, sir, heartily!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Sixth Citizen
initial speech: He has done nobly, and cannot go without any honest man's voice.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Seventh Citizen
initial speech: Therefore let him be consul: the gods give him joy, and make him good friend to the people!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: All Citizens
initial speech: Amen, amen. God save thee, noble consul!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Citizens
initial speech: No, no; no man saw 'em.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Senators, &C
initial speech: We'll surety him.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: AEdile
initial speech: Peace, peace!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: A Patrician
initial speech: This man has marr'd his fortune.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Patrician
initial speech: I would they were abed!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Both Tribunes
initial speech: Well, say. Peace, ho!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Roman
initial speech: I know you well, sir, and you know me: your name, I think, is Adrian.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Volsce
initial speech: It is so, sir: truly, I have forgot you.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Citizen
initial speech: And you.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: First Servingman
initial speech: Wine, wine, wine! What service is here! I think our fellows are asleep.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Second Servingman
initial speech: Where's Cotus? my master calls for him. Cotus!

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Third Servingman
initial speech: What fellow's this?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: Young MARCIUS
initial speech: A' shall not tread on me; I'll run away till I am bigger, but then I'll fight.

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
speaker: First Conspirator
initial speech: How is it with our general?

title: The Tragedy of Coriolanus
